<br>
The UK government’s decision to grant British Energy (BE) a short-term loan of up to 410 million pounds (GBP) has averted for the time being fears that the UK nuclear generator might face imminent bankruptcy, and has paved the way for a longer-term corporate restructuring .<br>
<br>
 <br>
But what lies behind the current financial crisis at a company that has received several awards for its innovative, and highly profitable, nuclear investment strategy in North America, but increasingly has difficulties making ends meet at home? <br>
One short-term ‘catalyst’ for BE’s liquidity problems was the unplanned shut-down of its Torness-1 nuclear unit in Scotland, in the wake of similar operational problems earlier this year at both Torness-2 and Dungeness-B . The announcement led to a sharp fall in BE’s share value, after the company confirmed that its projected UK nuclear output would be in the region of 63 terawatt-hours (TWh), compared with its original projection of 67.5 TWh for fiscal 2002-2003. In addition, ongoing talks with fellow UK nuclear company BNFL about a possible cash-generative contract to run its Magnox nuclear plants have so far failed to reach a mutually satisfactory conclusion. <br>
However, the roots of BE’s current problems are more fundamental – and largely specific to the UK market. Executive chairman Robin Jeffrey summarised this view in a speech this year, when he pointed to the profitability of BE’s US and Canadian operations, but added: “(In the UK), we are being squeezed between a rock and a hard place – our spent fuel contracts and electricity market prices”. Below, NucNet outlines some of the key issues: <br>
Electricity prices: Wholesale electricity prices in the UK have fallen sharply over the past two years, due to a mixture of over-capacity, diversified plant ownership (increased competition) and the introduction of the so-called New Electricity Trading Arrangements (NETA): <br>
· Dr Jeffrey told the BE annual general assembly in July that wholesale prices had dropped from GBP 20 per megawatt-hour (MWh) to GBP 17 per MWh in the past 18 months alone. Based on total BE output of 75 TWh per year (including the Eggborough coal-fired plant), that drop would translate into a reduction of GBP 225 million in BE’s pre-tax profit. <br>
· BE’s nuclear power stations have not been the only UK generators to feel the financial effects of such price cuts. Wholesale prices are now at or below the marginal costs of coal-fired plants; at least one coal-fired generator has had to close down on financial grounds within the past year, and BE was forced to write down the asset value of its own (coal-fired) Eggborough plant by some GBP 300 million at the end of fiscal 2001. Electricity market expert William Heller, the European head of US-owned generator Edison, commented nearly a year ago that ‘market fundamentals’, combined with NETA, had pushed UK wholesale prices so low that there was no longer any financial return possible on capital investment in new generating plant – be it nuclear, renewable, coal-fired or gas-fired. <br>
· However, BE has been even harder hit than other UK generators. Because of the base-load nature of its nuclear plants, BE is particularly vulnerable under the new system – it has little choice but to keep plants operating, and is therefore obliged to accept whatever price is offered for output. Also, unlike its main competitors, BE has no major trading arm, and is unable to compensate for low wholesale prices by selling large volumes to retail customers at more favourable prices. <br>
Spent fuel contracts: If falling electricity prices represent BE’s ‘rock’, its ongoing spent fuel reprocessing commitments with BNFL are seen by the company as its ‘hard place’: <br>
· BE said last year in a submission to a government policy review that, under current market conditions, direct storage of advanced gas-cooled reactor (AGR) fuel would be “considerably cheaper” than reprocessing. It has since stated publicly that BNFL continues to be responsible both for managing its spent fuel and for deciding how best to do so (i.e. whether or not to reprocess). BE continues to hold discussions with BNFL aimed at agreeing renegotiated terms for its existing (index-linked) spent fuel management contracts, which would “better reflect current market realities”. <br>
· Referring to BE’s interim financial results in November 2001, Dr Jeffrey said: “Had direct disposal been the UK policy on terms analogous to the US, then BE would have been in profit in the UK. Conversely, had reprocessing been adopted in the US, then our North American profit would have been wiped out. It is as simple as that.” <br>
Property taxes/rates: BE recently appealed to the European Commission to investigate what it sees as an “unfair economic penalty” on UK nuclear generation, in the form of higher property rates charged to its nuclear plants. The higher rates – GBP 14 000 per month, compared to GBP 9500 per month for both gas and coal generators and GBP 5000 per month for wind farms – mean that BE is effectively paying a total of GBP 20 million more per year compared to its competitors. The company says this leads to a clear “distortion of competition” in a “highly-competitive” electricity market, which it simply “cannot afford”. <br>
Climate change tax: Despite being the UK’s “leading carbon-free energy producer”, nuclear power generation is subject since last year to the ‘climate change levy’, a tax on business that is calculated at 0.43 pence per kWh for electricity generation, with exemptions only for wind and solar. BE estimates that full exemption for all of its nuclear generation could save up to GBP 270 million per year, split between the company and its customers. It estimates its own potential savings if exempted from the levy at between GBP 80 and 100 million per year. <br>
BE has been urging the government for some time now to address these issues, along with a number of related, but longer-term issues. These include: <br>
· The need for fundamental changes to the regulatory and planning framework to encourage investment in new-build, along the lines of current changes in the US. <br>
· The need for greater government investment in nuclear training and R&amp;D. <br>
· The need to replace the planned ‘obligation’ to purchase minimum quantities of renewable electricity with a more general ‘carbon-free purchase obligation’. (Under the planned legislation, customers will have to purchase 10% of their electricity from renewable sources by 2010 or pay a penalty of GBP 30 per MWh on their ‘shortfall’. In return, renewables operators will receive a ‘premium’, currently set around the same level). <br>
UK energy minister Brian Wilson was quoted recently as saying that a policy review with regard to several issues – in particular, the impact of NETA and the climate change levy – should be given serious consideration. The government is currently expected to publish a White Paper on energy policy later this year, but it is not yet clear whether any near-term action is now likely. <br>
