<br>
It is an end user consumption tax. It is NOT a supply levy.<br>
<br>
It is designed to encourage energy efficiency by industrial and commercial end users.<br>
<br>
It does allow exemptions for SOME contracted renewable energy supplies.  In particular, it does not allow an exemption for large hydro. <br>
<br>
Nuclear suppliers do not qualify for the exemption, just as large hydro does not. <br>
<br>
The levy is 2/3 of a penny per kilowatt hour. British Energy is asking for an exemption. This tiny subsidy still would not go anywhere towards helping B.E. bail itself out of its nuclear collapse. <br>
The article starting this thread points out that British Energy &quot;estimates its own potential savings if exempted from the levy at between GBP 80 and 100 million per year. &quot;<br>
<br>
